# Project Structure Guide

## Directory Structure

- `src/` - Source code
  - `apis/` - API definitions and request functions
  - `assets/` - Static assets (images, fonts, etc.)
  - `components/` - React components
    - `base/` - Base components (buttons, inputs, etc.)
    - `business/` - Business-specific components
    - `common/` - Common reusable components
    - `providers/` - Context providers
    - `debug/` - Debug-related components
  - `const/` - Constants
  - `enhance/` - Enhancements
  - `hooks/` - Custom React Hooks
  - `layouts/` - Page layout components
  - `models/` - Data models
  - `pages/` - Pages
  - `premium/` - Premium features
  - `routes/` - Route configuration
  - `services/` - Service layer (business logic)
  - `stores/` - State management (Zustand/MobX)
  - `styles/` - Global styles
  - `types/` - TypeScript type definitions
  - `utils/` - Utilities

## Naming Conventions

1. Use kebab-case for files/directories (e.g., `user-profile.tsx`)
2. Use PascalCase for component files (e.g., `UserProfile.tsx`)
3. Prefix Hook files with `use` (e.g., `useUserData.ts`)
4. Use `.d.ts` or `.types.ts` for type definition files

## File Organization

1. Component directory structure:
   ```
   ComponentName/
     ├── index.tsx       # Main component file
     ├── style.ts        # Styles (using createStyle)
     ├── types.ts        # Type definitions
     ├── utils.ts        # Component utilities
     └── __tests__/      # Tests
       └── index.test.tsx  # Test file
   ```

2. Page directories follow a similar pattern and may include subcomponents

## Import/Export Conventions

1. Prefer named exports over default exports
2. Re-export modules from index files
3. Import order: external libs > internal modules > relative modules
